revision.text:
{{one source|date=February 2015}} The '''26th [[National Geographic Bee]]''' was held in [[Washington, D.C.]] on May 21, 2014, sponsored by the [[National Geographic Society]]. {{Spelling bee | name = 26th National Geographic Bee <!-- Commented out: | image = NationalGeographicBeeOfficialLogo.png --> | caption = | date = May 19–21, 2014 | location = [[Washington, D.C.]] | winner = Akhil Rekulapelli | age = 13 | residence = [[Dulles, Virginia]] | word = | contestants = 54 | moderator = | Preceded by = [[25th National Geographic Bee]] | Followed by = [[27th National Geographic Bee]] }} Eighth-grader Akhil Rekulapelli, from [[Loudoun County, Virginia]] won the competition, beating out 52 other competitors representing the 50 U.S. states, Pacific territories, and [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] dependent schools.<ref>[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2014/05/140521-geography-bee-national-geographic-world-scholarship-students/]</ref>
In 2014, a record number of 9 perfect scores in the national preliminary competition was recorded. As a result, a sudden-death tiebreaker took place between 8 state representatives including contestants from Alabama, Utah, Texas, Maryland, Virginia, Illinois and Washington.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}
Akhil Rekulapelli, the 2014 National Geographic Bee Champion, received a $50,000 scholarship, a lifetime membership to the National Geographic Society, and a trip for 2 to the Galapagos Islands. Ameya Mujumdar, the second-place finisher received $25,000. Tuvya Bergeson-Michelson, the third-place finisher received $10,000, and Pranit Nanda the fourth-place finisher received $1,000. Other top ten finishers received $500.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}
