'''Anglo-America''' most often refers to a region in the [[Americas]] in which [[English language|English]] is a main language and [[British culture]] and the [[British Empire]] have had significant historical, ethnic, linguistic and cultural impact.<ref name=eb>"Anglo-America", vol. 1, Micropædia, ''Encyclopædia Britannica'', 15th ed., Chicago: Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc., 1990. {{ISBN|0-85229-511-1}}.</ref> [[Anglo]]-America is distinct from [[Latin America]], a region of the Americas where [[Romance languages]] ([[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] and [[French language|French]]) are prevalent.<ref name=eb />

== Geographic region ==
{{See also|Official bilingualism in Canada|English-speaking Quebecker|English in Puerto Rico}}

The term ''Anglo-America'' frequently refers specifically to the [[United States]] and [[Canada]], by far the two most populous English-speaking countries in North America.<ref name=c>"[http://www.bartleby.com/65/na/NAmer.html North America]" [http://www.bartleby.com/65 ''The Columbia Encyclopedia''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206222118/http://www.bartleby.com/65 |date=February 6, 2007 }}, 6th ed. 2001-5. New York: Columbia University Press.</ref> Other areas composing the [[Commonwealth Caribbean|Anglophone Caribbean]] include territories of the former [[British West Indies]], [[Belize]], [[Bermuda]], and [[Guyana]].

Two notable territories with substantial non-Anglophone majorities are nonetheless often included in Anglo-America for linguistical reasons. In [[French language in Canada|Canada]], the [[francophone]] province of [[Quebec]], [[Acadia]] in [[New Brunswick]] and a part of [[Cochrane District]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muturzikin.com/cartesusa/canada.htm|title=Carte linguistique du Canada / Linguistic map of Canada|author=mutur zikin|work=muturzikin.com|accessdate=22 September 2015}}</ref> are sometimes considered part of Anglo-America for [[culture of Quebec|cultural]], [[economy of Quebec|economic]], [[geography of Quebec|geographical]], [[history of Quebec|historical]], and [[politics of Quebec|political]] reasons. Similarly, Spanish-speaking [[Puerto Rico]] is considered part of Anglo-America because of its status as an [[Unincorporated territories of the United States|unincorporated territory]] of the [[Political divisions of the United States|United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/NPTable?_bm=y&-geo_id=04000US72&-qr_name=ACS_2009_5YR_G00_NPPR01&-ds_name=&-redoLog=false |title=2005–2009 Population and Housing Narrative Profile for Puerto Rico |accessdate=May 19, 2011 |date=2005–2009 |work=U.S. Census Narrative Profile |publisher=U.S. Census |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008150642/http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/NPTable?_bm=y&-geo_id=04000US72&-qr_name=ACS_2009_5YR_G00_NPPR01&-ds_name=&-redoLog=false |archivedate=October 8, 2011 |df= }}</ref> Conversely, [[Sint Eustatius]], [[Sint Maarten]], and [[Saba]] are not typically included in Anglo-America, despite their English-speaking majorities, because they are constituent countries or ''[[Public body (Netherlands)|public bodies]]'' that form part of the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Kingdom]] of the [[Netherlands]].

